05472nam a22007215i 9780801460722DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20112011nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979575381  a97808014607227 a10.7591/97808014607222doi  a(DE-B1597)478618  a(OCoLC)865509006  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aJN6693.5.M5bG58 2016 7aHIS0320002bisacsh04a320.54089009472231 aGiuliano, Elise, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aConstructing Grievance :bEthnic Nationalism in Russia's Republics /cElise Giuliano. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (248 p.) :b1 line drawing, 1 map, 23 tables, 9 charts/graphs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tTables -- tPreface -- t1. Ethnic Entrepreneurs, Ordinary People, and Group Grievance -- t2. Variation in Mass Nationalism across Russia’s Republics -- t3. Does Structure Matter? Local Labor Markets and Social Mobility -- t4. Supporting National Sovereignty in Tatarstan -- t5. Nationalism in a Socialist Company Town: Tatars, Russians, and the Kamskii Automobile Works in Naberezhnye Chelny -- t6. Ethnic Entrepreneurs and the Construction of Group Grievance: Tuva, Mari El, and Komi Compared -- t7. Secessionism from the Bottom Up: Democratization, Nationalism, and Local Accountability in Russia -- t8. Lessons from Russia: A Critical View of the Relationship between Ethnic Elite Claims and Mass Interests -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDemands for national independence among ethnic minorities around the world suggest the power of nationalism. Contemporary nationalist movements can quickly attract fervent followings, but they can just as rapidly lose support. In Constructing Grievance, Elise Giuliano asks why people with ethnic identities throw their support behind nationalism in some cases but remain quiescent in others. Popular support for nationalism, Giuliano contends, is often fleeting. It develops as part of the process of political mobilization—a process that itself transforms the meaning of ethnic identity. She compares sixteen ethnic republics of the Russian Federation, where nationalist mobilization varied widely during the early 1990s despite a common Soviet inheritance. Drawing on field research in the republic of Tatarstan, socioeconomic statistical data, and a comparative discourse analysis of local newspapers, Giuliano argues that people respond to nationalist leaders after developing a group grievance. Ethnic grievances, however, are not simply present or absent among a given population based on societal conditions. Instead, they develop out of the interaction between people's lived experiences and the specific messages that nationalist entrepreneurs put forward concerning ethnic group disadvantage.In Russia, Giuliano shows, ethnic grievances developed rapidly in certain republics in the late Soviet era when messages articulated by nationalist leaders about ethnic inequality in local labor markets resonated with people's experience of growing job insecurity in a contracting economy. In other republics, however, where nationalist leaders focused on articulating other issues, such as cultural and language problems facing the ethnic group, group grievances failed to develop, and popular support for nationalism stalled. People with ethnic identities, Giuliano concludes, do not form political interest groups primed to support ethnic politicians and movements for national secession.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aMinoritiesxPolitical activityzRussia (Federation). 0aNationalismzRussia (Federation). 0aSelf-determination, N